VALUES
(1, 31, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'and if he said thus, The ringstraked shall be thy hire;', 85, 140, 'question', 'Trusting God''s Plan', 'In light of Jacob''s experiences, how does the promise of God’s provision encourage you to trust in His plan for your life? What does it mean for you personally that God can bring about His will even in the midst of human deception or manipulation?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'then bare all the cattle ringstraked.', 141, 178, 'greek', 'Nature''s Response to God''s Will', 'While the Old Testament primarily uses Hebrew, the concept of creation responding to God''s word is echoed in the New Testament. The Greek word for ''creation'' is κτίσις (ktisis, G2937) - creation, creature, act of creating. This emphasizes that all creation is under God''s authority and responds to His commands, demonstrating the interconnectedness of divine will and the natural order.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2937", "description": "Greek term for ''creation''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Thus God hath taken away the cattle of your father, and given them to me.', 0, 73, 'connection', 'Divine Providence', 'This verse resonates with the theme of divine providence found in Genesis 50:20, where Joseph states, ''You meant evil against me, but God meant it for good.'' Both passages highlight God''s sovereignty in orchestrating events for His purposes, even amidst human deception and conflict. This connection emphasizes that God''s plans prevail despite human actions.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 50:20", "description": "Joseph''s recognition of God''s sovereignty over his life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Thus God hath taken away the cattle of your father, and given them to me.', 0, 73, 'theology', 'Sovereignty of God', 'This passage suggests a significant theological principle regarding God''s sovereignty. Many scholars believe this reflects the idea that God is actively involved in the affairs of humanity, orchestrating outcomes according to His will and purpose. The transfer of wealth from Laban to Jacob underscores the belief that God rewards faithfulness and integrity, a common theme throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Thus God hath taken away the cattle of your father, and given them to me.', 0, 73, 'question', 'Understanding God''s Provision', 'In what ways have you recognized God''s hand in the redistribution of resources in your own life? How does this understanding shape your perspective on stewardship and trust in God’s provision?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'that I lifted up mine eyes', 59, 85, 'connection', 'Vision and Revelation', 'This phrase echoes the theme of divine revelation found in other biblical narratives, such as Genesis 21:19, where God opens Hagar''s eyes to see a well of water. The lifting of eyes symbolizes awareness of God''s presence and intervention. Recognizing God’s revelation can lead to transformative experiences in our spiritual journey.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 21:19", "description": "Hagar''s eyes are opened to a source of sustenance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'and saw in a dream', 87, 105, 'theology', 'Divine Communication', 'This passage suggests that God communicates through dreams, a concept supported by the biblical narrative and theological interpretations. Many scholars believe this reflects God''s sovereignty in guiding His people, as seen in Joseph''s dreams in Genesis 37. Dreams serve as a medium for divine messages, revealing God''s plans.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'the rams which leaped upon the cattle', 120, 157, 'question', 'Symbolism of the Rams', 'What do the rams symbolize in the context of Jacob''s journey and God’s promise? Considering the behavior of the rams may lead to deeper understanding of God''s providence in our lives. How do we recognize the ways God provides for us in unexpected forms?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And the angel of God spake unto me in a dream, saying, Jacob: And I said, Here am I.', 0, 84, 'connection', 'Divine Encounters', 'This verse parallels Genesis 22:11, where an angel calls out to Abraham during a critical moment of faith. Both instances highlight how God communicates through dreams and angels, demonstrating His active involvement in the lives of the patriarchs. Understanding these encounters deepens our appreciation for divine guidance throughout biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 22:11", "description": "Similar divine intervention with Abraham"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'saying, Jacob: And I said, Here am I.', 47, 84, 'question', 'Response to God''s Call', 'What does Jacob''s immediate response, ''Here am I,'' reveal about his readiness to listen and obey God''s direction? How can we cultivate a similar willingness to respond when we sense God''s prompting in our own lives?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'the angel of God spake unto me', 4, 34, 'theology', 'The Role of Angels', 'This passage suggests that angels serve as messengers of God, communicating His will to humanity. Many scholars believe that understanding the angelic role in Scripture can enhance our view of how God interacts with His creation, emphasizing that divine communication is often mediated through spiritual beings.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'the angel of God spake unto me', 4, 34, 'greek', 'Angel in Greek', 'ἄγγελος (angelos, G32) - messenger, envoy. This term signifies a being sent to deliver a message, underscoring the role of angels in God''s communication with humans, as seen in this divine encounter.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G32", "description": "Strong''s number for ''angelos''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'Lift up now thine eyes', 13, 35, 'theology', 'Divine Revelation', 'This phrase invites reflection on the nature of divine revelation. Many scholars believe that God often calls His people to ''lift their eyes'' to see His providence and guidance in their lives. This act of looking up symbolizes faith and attentiveness to God''s direction, encouraging believers to maintain a spiritual perspective amid challenges.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'all the rams which leap upon the cattle are ringstraked, speckled, and grisled', 46, 124, 'connection', 'God''s Sovereignty in Provision', 'This description of the rams connects to Romans 8:28, which states, ''And we know that in all things God works for the good of those who love him.'' The specificity of the rams'' markings signifies God''s detailed awareness of Jacob''s situation and His active role in providing for him, reinforcing the theme of divine providence throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 8:28", "description": "God''s sovereignty in working for the good of His people."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'for I have seen all that Laban doeth unto thee', 126, 172, 'question', 'Understanding God''s Awareness', 'What does it mean to you that God sees all that happens in your life, including the actions of others against you? How can this understanding shape your response to injustice or hardship?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'I am the God of Beth–el', 0, 23, 'connection', 'Significance of Beth-el', 'The mention of Beth-el recalls Jacob''s earlier encounter with God in Genesis 28:10-22, where he had a dream of a ladder reaching to heaven. This reinforces the sacredness of the site, symbolizing God''s covenantal presence and promises to Jacob. The connection emphasizes that God reaffirms His commitment to Jacob and his descendants.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 28:10-22", "description": "Jacob''s dream at Beth-el signifies God''s promises."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'where thou anointedst the pillar', 25, 57, 'theology', 'Anointing as Consecration', 'The act of anointing the pillar signifies consecration and the establishment of a sacred space. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical theme that God often uses physical symbols (like oil or stones) to signify His presence and blessing, establishing a tangible connection between the divine and the earthly.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of anointing in biblical contexts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'now arise, get thee out from this land', 97, 135, 'question', 'Call to Action', 'What does God''s command to ''arise'' and ''get thee out'' reveal about His plans for our lives? How might this challenge us to leave behind what is comfortable or familiar to pursue God''s calling?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'and return unto the land of thy kindred', 137, 176, 'greek', 'Return and Renewal', 'שוב (shuv, H7725) - to return, turn back. This Hebrew term emphasizes the idea of returning not just physically but spiritually as well, suggesting a move towards reconciliation with one''s roots and fulfilling God''s covenantal promises.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7725", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''to return.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Is there yet any portion or inheritance for us in our father’s house?', 48, 117, 'connection', 'Inheritance Themes', 'This question reflects a profound concern for inheritance, echoing themes found in Numbers 27:8, where daughters are granted inheritance rights. The connection illustrates the evolving understanding of women''s rights within the covenant community. Rachel and Leah''s inquiry signifies their awareness of their status in the family legacy, which aligns with God''s broader plan for inclusivity in His promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 27:8", "description": "Highlights inheritance rights granted to women in Israel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Is there yet any portion or inheritance for us in our father’s house?', 48, 117, 'theology', 'Women''s Rights in Scripture', 'This passage suggests a significant theological concept regarding the value and rights of women in God''s plan. Many scholars believe that Rachel and Leah''s question about their inheritance reflects the broader biblical narrative that affirms women''s roles and rights within God''s covenant. This moment marks a critical point in understanding how God elevates the status of women, making them active participants in His promises.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Is there yet any portion or inheritance for us in our father’s house?', 48, 117, 'question', 'Reflection on Inheritance', 'What does this inquiry about inheritance reveal about our understanding of belonging and identity within God’s family? How does recognizing our spiritual inheritance in Christ shape our relationship with God and with one another?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Is there yet any portion or inheritance for us in our father’s house?', 48, 117, 'greek', 'Inheritance Concept', 'נחלה (nachalah, H5159) - inheritance, possession. This term emphasizes the idea of a rightful share or portion, underscoring Rachel and Leah''s desire for recognition and security in their familial legacy. Their reference to ''inheritance'' highlights the significance of belonging and the hope for a future beyond their current circumstances.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5159", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for inheritance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Are we not counted of him strangers?', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Strangers in the Land', 'The question posed by Rachel and Leah echoes sentiments found in Exodus 22:21, where it states, ''You shall not wrong a sojourner or oppress him, for you were sojourners in the land of Egypt.'' This connection highlights the theme of alienation and the treatment of outsiders, reflecting the broader biblical narrative about justice and compassion. Rachel and Leah’s sense of being treated as strangers emphasizes their marginalized status in their father''s house, paralleling the Israelites'' experiences in Egypt.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 22:21", "description": "Highlights the biblical theme of how sojourners should be treated."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'for he hath sold us, and hath quite devoured also our money.', 37, 97, 'theology', 'God''s Provision vs. Human Greed', 'This passage suggests a theological reflection on the consequences of greed and the exploitation of family ties. Many scholars believe that the experience of Rachel and Leah serves as an allegory for how human relationships can be corrupted by selfishness, contrasting with God''s provision for His people. It invites readers to consider how they honor family and steward resources, aligning with the biblical call to treat others with love and fairness.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Are we not counted of him strangers?', 0, 36, 'question', 'Identity and Belonging', 'What does it mean to feel like a stranger in your own family? How can this verse challenge you to reflect on your own relationships and the ways you may feel marginalized or disconnected? Consider how God views your identity and belonging as His child, and how this perspective can reshape your understanding of familial ties.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'for he hath sold us, and hath quite devoured also our money.', 37, 97, 'greek', 'Sold and Devoured', 'מָכַר (makhar, H4376) - to sell. This Hebrew term reflects not just a transaction but a deeper sense of loss and betrayal. The use of ''devoured'' indicates complete consumption, portraying the emotional and financial devastation felt by Rachel and Leah. These words underscore the harsh realities of their situation and the extent of their father''s exploitation.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4376", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''to sell.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'For all the riches which God hath taken from our father', 0, 55, 'connection', 'Divine Provision Theme', 'This phrase connects to Job 1:21, where Job acknowledges that God gives and takes away. Both passages reflect the sovereignty of God over material wealth and the understanding that what is gained or lost is ultimately under His control. This theme encourages believers to trust in God''s provision regardless of their circumstances.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Job 1:21", "description": "Job''s acknowledgment of God''s sovereignty over wealth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'that is ours, and our children’s', 57, 89, 'theology', 'Generational Inheritance', 'This passage suggests a theological principle of inheritance in the biblical context, where blessings are meant to extend beyond the individual to future generations. Many scholars believe that God''s promises and provisions are not only for us but are intended to benefit our descendants, emphasizing the importance of faith and stewardship in family lines.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'whatsoever God hath said unto thee, do.', 101, 140, 'question', 'Obedience to God''s Call', 'What does it mean to fully commit to doing ''whatsoever God hath said''? How can we discern God''s voice in our lives, and what steps are we willing to take in obedience? This reflection invites us to examine our own responsiveness to God''s direction.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Then Jacob rose up, and set his sons and his wives upon camels;', 0, 63, 'connection', 'Departure Motif', 'Jacob''s departure with his family parallels other significant departures in Scripture, such as Abraham leaving Haran (Genesis 12:1) and the Israelites fleeing Egypt (Exodus 12:31). These moments signify divine direction and the fulfillment of God''s promises. The act of gathering family and possessions highlights God’s providence in guiding His people to new beginnings.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:1", "description": "Abraham''s call to leave his homeland."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 12:31", "description": "Israelites'' departure from Egypt."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Then Jacob rose up, and set his sons and his wives upon camels;', 0, 63, 'theology', 'Family Leadership', 'This verse illustrates Jacob''s role as a leader and protector of his family, a theme that resonates throughout Scripture. Many scholars believe that patriarchal leadership is a model for familial responsibility in the Christian faith, where leaders are called to guide, nurture, and protect their families in faith and obedience to God.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Then Jacob rose up, and set his sons and his wives upon camels;', 0, 63, 'question', 'Purpose of Departure', 'What might Jacob''s decision to leave signify about his trust in God''s promises? In what ways can we discern God''s leading in our own lives when faced with significant transitions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Then Jacob rose up, and set his sons and his wives upon camels;', 0, 63, 'greek', 'Leadership in Action', 'Although this verse is primarily in Hebrew, the concept of ''rise up'' can also be explored in the Greek translation of the Old Testament (Septuagint). In Greek, the word for ''rise up'' is ''ἀναστῇ'' (anastē, G450), which signifies not only physical rising but also the notion of taking action or initiative, reflecting Jacob''s proactive leadership.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G450", "description": "Greek term for ''rise up'' indicating initiative."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'all his cattle, and all his goods which he had gotten', 20, 73, 'connection', 'God''s Provision', 'This phrase connects to Deuteronomy 8:18, where it is stated that God gives the power to get wealth. Jacob''s departure with his possessions reflects God''s blessing on his labor in Padan-aram. This highlights the biblical theme of God providing for His people as they obey Him, reinforcing the notion that material blessings can be a sign of divine favor.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 8:18", "description": "God''s provision for His people"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'for to go to Isaac his father in the land of Canaan', 137, 188, 'theology', 'Returning to Promise', 'This passage suggests the theological significance of returning to the promised land. Many scholars believe that Jacob''s journey back to Canaan symbolizes the fulfillment of God''s covenant and His faithfulness to Abraham''s descendants. It reflects the overarching biblical narrative of God''s redemptive plan through His chosen people.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'for to go to Isaac his father', 137, 166, 'question', 'Father-Son Relationship', 'What does Jacob''s desire to return to his father Isaac reveal about the importance of familial relationships in our spiritual journeys? How does this dynamic influence your understanding of obedience to God’s calling in your life?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'which he had gotten in Padan–aram', 102, 135, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Getting''', 'קָנָה (qanah, H7069) - to acquire, create, or own. This term underscores the active participation in the process of gaining wealth and possessions. It implies that Jacob''s success was not merely by chance but involved effort and divine favor in the land of Padan-aram, reflecting God''s providence in his labor.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7069", "description": "Hebrew word for ''to acquire''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Rachel had stolen the images that were her father’s.', 39, 91, 'connection', 'Idolatry in Scripture', 'Rachel''s theft of her father''s household gods highlights the ongoing theme of idolatry in the Bible. This act connects to Genesis 35:2, where Jacob instructs his household to put away foreign gods. The significance lies in understanding the struggle against idolatry that permeates the narrative, illustrating how even the patriarch''s family was not immune to the lure of idols.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 35:2", "description": "Jacob''s call to remove idols from his household."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Rachel had stolen the images that were her father’s.', 39, 91, 'theology', 'The Nature of Idolatry', 'Many scholars believe that Rachel''s actions symbolize a deeper spiritual struggle within families and communities regarding loyalty to God versus cultural practices. The act of stealing household gods reflects not only personal conflict but also the broader challenge of faithfulness to the true God amidst the influences of surrounding cultures.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on idolatry and its implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Laban went to shear his sheep:', 4, 34, 'question', 'Timing and Divine Providence', 'What might God be orchestrating in the seemingly mundane detail of Laban''s absence during Jacob''s departure? How does this moment illustrate God''s providence in guiding Jacob''s escape and fulfilling His promise to him?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Rachel had stolen the images that were her father’s.', 39, 91, 'greek', 'Household Gods', 'תרפים (teraphim, H8655) - household gods or idols, often associated with divination or ancestor worship. Rachel''s act of stealing these reflects the tension between her loyalty to her husband and the cultural practices of her family.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8655", "description": "Strong''s number for ''teraphim''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'stole away unawares', 10, 29, 'connection', 'Deceptive Actions', 'Jacob''s act of ''stealing away unawares'' can be compared to other instances of deception in Scripture, such as David''s feigned madness in 1 Samuel 21:13. Both narratives highlight human cunning in navigating complex relationships. This connection emphasizes the lengths to which individuals might go to escape difficult situations, reflecting the moral complexities of human behavior.', 'arrow.triangle.branch', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 21:13", "description": "David pretends to be mad to escape danger"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'unawares', 21, 29, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Unawares''', 'This phrase in Hebrew, גָּנַב (ganav, H1589), means ''to steal'' or ''to deceive.'' It conveys not just a physical act of theft but also an element of cunning or stealth. Understanding this term provides insight into Jacob''s motivations and the dynamics of his relationship with Laban, highlighting themes of trust and betrayal.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1589", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''ganav''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'in that he told him not that he fled', 51, 87, 'theology', 'The Nature of Deception', 'Many scholars believe this verse illustrates the complexity of human relationships and the moral implications of deceit. Jacob''s choice to flee without informing Laban raises questions about trust, accountability, and the consequences of our actions. It suggests a tension between divine guidance and human ethical standards, prompting reflection on how we navigate our own relationships.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on the ethical dimensions of Jacob''s actions"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Jacob stole away unawares', 4, 29, 'question', 'Reflecting on Escape', 'What does Jacob''s decision to flee without warning reveal about his relationship with Laban? How might we apply this lesson about honesty and communication in our own lives, especially when faced with difficult decisions?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'So he fled with all that he had;', 0, 32, 'theology', 'Faith in Action', 'This phrase illustrates Jacob''s decisive faith in God’s promise, as he leaves behind everything familiar in pursuit of God’s calling. Many scholars believe that Jacob''s flight signifies a pivotal moment of trust, reflecting the broader biblical theme of reliance on divine guidance amidst uncertainty.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'passed over the river,', 53, 75, 'connection', 'River Symbolism', 'The act of passing over the river can be cross-referenced with Joshua 3:14-17, where Israel crosses the Jordan River into the Promised Land. This connection highlights the theme of transition and divine deliverance, indicating that Jacob''s journey is not just physical but also spiritual as he moves towards God’s promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 3:14-17", "description": "Israel''s crossing symbolizes divine guidance and new beginnings."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'set his face toward the mount Gilead.', 80, 117, 'question', 'Direction of Focus', 'What does it mean to set one’s face toward a destination in the context of faith? Consider how Jacob’s focus on Mount Gilead represents a commitment to follow God’s leading. How does this challenge you to set your own direction based on God’s guidance in your life?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 31, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'And it was told Laban on the third day that Jacob was fled.', 0, 59, 'connection', 'Laban''s Pursuit of Jacob', 'This verse connects to Genesis 32:6, where Jacob learns that Esau is coming to meet him with 400 men. Both instances reveal the theme of familial conflict and pursuit. Laban''s pursuit of Jacob exemplifies the tension in their relationship, just as Esau''s approach signifies Jacob''s past sins catching up with him. Understanding the urgency and danger in these familial dynamics deepens our grasp of the narrative''s emotional weight.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 32:6", "description": "Illustrates another moment of familial tension and urgency in Jacob''s life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');